Base.Explanation: Create a group in Active Directory. The group is created in a Active Directory domain, organizational unit or other container. Optionally, you can specify the domain controller on which the group is created.

ArrayElement.Name: Domain
ArrayElement.Description: The name of the domain (DNS or NETBIOS style, e.g. tools4ever.com or TOOLS4EVER) where the group will be created. Optionally you can specify the property 'Organizational Unit-Container'. If you specify a value for this property, do not specify a value for property 'LDAP-container' since this specification takes precedence.

ArrayElement.Name: Organizational Unit-Container
ArrayElement.Description: The name of the Organizational Unit-Container where the group must be created (example: Students or Division_AStudents\Group1). If you specify a value for this property, you should also specify a value for the 'Domain' property. If you specify a value for this property, do not specify a value for property 'LDAP-container' since that specification overrules this specification.

ArrayElement.Name: LDAP Container
ArrayElement.Description: The LDAP name of the organizational unit or container where the group must be created (example: cn=Marketing, cn=Tools4ever, cn=Com). You must specify either a value for this property or values for the properties 'Domain' and 'Organizational Unit-Container'. If values for both methods are specified, this method takes precedence.

ArrayElement.Name: Domain (controller)
ArrayElement.Description: Optional: The name of the domain controller or domain, used to access to the domain, container or organizational unit where the group must be created. If this value is not specified or the name of a domain is specified, the application creates the group on a domain controller that is to be determined by Active Directory (serverless binding). If a domain controller is specified, the group is explicitly created on the specified controller (server binding). In both cases, Active Directory will replicate the account information to all domain controllers in the Active Directory forests and domains.

ArrayElement.Name: Common Name
ArrayElement.Description: The 'CommonName' corresponds with the full name of the group. This name is most common used in Windows' user interfaces when showing names.

ArrayElement.Name: SAM-Account-Name
ArrayElement.Description: The pre-Windows 2000 group name without the (NETBIOS) domain name. In most cases the SAM-Account-Name is equal to the 'Common-Name' of the group. The name must be unique within the domain.

ArrayElement.Name: Description
ArrayElement.Description: The group comment. The field can contain a text of any length.

ArrayElement.Name: Local group
ArrayElement.Description: Set to 'Yes' if the group must become a (domain) local group (group scope: local). The group scope is determined by setting one of the following properties: 'Local group', 'Global group' or 'Universal group'.

ArrayElement.Name: Global group
ArrayElement.Description: Set to 'Yes' if the group must become a global group (group scope: global). The group scope is determined by setting one of the following properties: 'Local group', 'Global group' or 'Universal group'.

ArrayElement.Name: Universal group
ArrayElement.Description: Set to 'Yes' if the group must become a universal group (group scope: universal). The group scope is determined by setting one of the following properties: 'Local group', 'Global group' or 'Universal group'.

ArrayElement.Name: Security group
ArrayElement.Description: Set to 'Yes' if the group must become a security group. If this property is not specified (or set to 'No') the group becomes a distribution group.

ArrayElement.Name: No error if group already exists
ArrayElement.Description: If set to 'Yes', no error is generated when this action failes because the group already exists.

ArrayElement.Name: Group Object Distinguished Name
ArrayElement.Description: The Object Distinguished Name of the new group. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated by the application automatically. The 'Group Object Distinguished Name' is created by the Active Directory automatically when the group is created. Once the user group is created, you can store the Object Distinguished Name in a variable (%GroupODN%) and use the variable in subsequent actions.

ArrayElement.Name: Group Object
ArrayElement.Description: An internal data structure representing the group. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated automatically. This property can be used in other script actions, for instance to set additional attributes for the group.
